# Let's work with Q-Q plots to check the scaling that we can apply:

import scipy.stats as stat
import pylab
def plot_QQ(df,feature_1,feature_2,feature_3,feature_4,feature_5):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))#probplot is Q-Q plot
    plt.subplot(3,3,1)  #3 rows, 3 columns, 1st placement
    sns.distplot(df[feature_1])
    stat.probplot(df[feature_1],dist='norm',plot=pylab)
    plt.xlabel(feature_1)
    plt.subplot(3,3,2)
    stat.probplot(df[feature_2],dist='norm',plot=pylab)
    plt.xlabel(feature_2)
    plt.subplot(3,3,3)
    stat.probplot(df[feature_3],dist='norm',plot=pylab)
    plt.xlabel(feature_3)
    plt.subplot(3,3,7)
    stat.probplot(df[feature_4],dist='norm',plot=pylab)
    plt.xlabel(feature_4)
    plt.subplot(3,3,8)
    stat.probplot(df[feature_5],dist='norm',plot=pylab)
    plt.xlabel(feature_5)
    plt.show()

In [40]:
# Creating a function which creates new features and applies logarithmic , reciprocal, square root and
# exponential transformations to the same.
dataframe = df.copy()
def transform_feat(dataframe,feature):
    dataframe[feature+'_log'] = np.log(dataframe[feature])
    dataframe[feature+'_reciprocal'] = 1/dataframe[feature]
    dataframe[feature+'_sqrt'] = np.sqrt(dataframe[feature])
    dataframe[feature+'_exp'] = dataframe[feature]**(1/1.2)

Here in the above Q-Q plots we can clearly see that none of the distributions have successfully been transformed into a normal distribution by any of the above used transformations out of logarithmic , reciprocal, square root and exponential transformations. Therefor, we are going to use other methods of transfromation/scaling to scale the features into normal distributions.¶

We can apply Standardisation for scaling but before that we need to see the outliers as Standardisation does not perform well with outliers.¶

In [238]:
plt.figure(figsize=(11,11))

    ax = plt.subplot(3,3,plotnumber)
    df.boxplot(column=feature)
    plt.xlabel(feature)
    plotnumber += 1
plt.tight_layout()

Since, we have a lot of outliers present in the dataset, we will not use Standardisation/Normalization, whcih will be affected by the presence of outliers. Therefore, we need to use Robust Scaler.¶

As we can clearly see that even after applying the Robust Scaler, the distributions remain the same. Therefore, we will check with other transformations on the dataset. As a result, we are going to use the algorithms that are not highly dependent upon Normal distribution of the data.¶

As per the problem statement, distribution similarity as well as colinearity, the features which are highly colinear are:¶
Totalsteps, TotalDistance and TrackerDistance. Therefore, we can remove TrackerDistance and TotalDistance.¶
LoggedActivitiesDistance and SedentaryActiveDistance can be removed as it has max zero values.¶

Now, checking relationship between independent and dependent features:¶

In [109]:
for feature in df:
    plt.scatter(df[feature],df['Calories'])
    plt.title(f'Relationship between {feature} and Calories')
    plt.xlabel(feature)

As we can see here the relationships for 'Totalsteps', 'TotalDistance' and 'TrackerDistance' is with 'Calories' burnt is very similar and features like 'Id', 'ActivityDate' and 'LoggedActivitiesDistance' have almost no proper relationship with 'Calories'.Also, SedentaryActiveDistance has a lot of '0' values. Therefore, according to every analysis till now, we can remove the features:¶

'TotalDistance'
'TrackerDistance'
'Id'
'ActivityDate'
'LoggedActivitiesDistance'
'SedentaryActiveDistance' and
'Date' (which was just created to see the relationship for Calories burned per day)

After checking with multiple Train Test splits, clearly, SVR is not giving a good R2 score, mean absolute error or root mean squared error. Linear Regression is giving a model which is highly inconsistent. Therefore, to avoid inconsistency and a low R2 score, we are going to use the best fit model out of Random Forest and XgBoost. Here Xgboost provides the best R2 score and the least mean absolute error. To avoid any decrepancy we will use clusters to find best model of the two algorithms in each cluster.¶

However, root mean squared error in all cases does not provide a proper measurement. So, we will go with R2 score and Mean absolute error.¶

In the main code, clusters have been created to find the best model out of both XgBoost and Random Forest.¶

Note: Hyperparameter Tuning has not been performed on SVR as the R2 score is too low as compared to the other three models.¶
